Certainly! Here's an updated version of the state machine for the parsing algorithm that extracts a puzzle from a PGN file of a Lichess game:

```json
"puzzleTraining": {
  "stateMachine": [
    {
      "name": "ReadPGN",
      "description": "Read the PGN game",
      "nextState": "IdentifyPosition"
    },
    {
      "name": "IdentifyPosition",
      "description": "Identify a potential puzzle position",
      "nextState": "AnalyzePosition"
    },
    {
      "name": "AnalyzePosition",
      "description": "Analyze the potential puzzle position",
      "nextState": "ValidateSolution"
    },
    {
      "name": "ValidateSolution",
      "description": "Validate the puzzle solution",
      "nextState": "ExtractPuzzle",
      "conditions": "NoValidSolution"
    },
    {
      "name": "ValidateSolution",
      "description": "Validate the puzzle solution",
      "nextState": "ContinueExtraction",
      "conditions": "ValidSolution"
    },
    {
      "name": "ExtractPuzzle",
      "description": "Extract the puzzle",
      "nextState": "ContinueExtraction"
    },
    {
      "name": "ContinueExtraction",
      "description": "Continue extracting puzzles or end",
      "nextState": "",
      "conditions": "MorePositions"
    }
  ]
}
```

In this updated version, each state is represented as an object with three properties: `name`, `description`, and `nextState`. The `name` property represents the name of the state, the `description` property provides a description of what happens in that state, and the `nextState` property indicates the name of the next state to transition to.

Additionally, the `ValidateSolution` state has two possible transitions based on conditions. If there is no valid solution, it transitions to the `ExtractPuzzle` state. If there is a valid solution, it transitions to the `ContinueExtraction` state.

The `ContinueExtraction` state serves as an exit point from the state machine when there are no more positions to extract.

